On {{ill|March 4, 1927|ja|1927th year 3月4日|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}, a full revision (Showa 2, Imperial Ordinance No. 25)<ref>[https://dl.ndl.go.jp/info:ndljp/pid/2956510/1 官報 1927th year 3月4日]</ref> added the {{ill|Meiji Setsu|ja|明治節|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|November 3|ja|11月3日|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}). Following the demise of Emperor Taisho and the accession of {{ill|Emperor Showa|ja|昭和天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}, the {{ill|Previous Emperor Festival|ja|先帝祭|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}} was moved from the Meiji Emperor Festival to the Taisho Emperor Festival ({{ill|December 25|ja|12月25日|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}), and the Tenchōsetsu was moved to {{ill|April 29|ja|4月29日|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}. The Tenchōsetsu holiday added in 1913 was abolished due to its summer timing. The Meiji Setsu was introduced to offset this loss, maintaining the total number of holidays.

On {{ill|July 20, 1948|ja|1948th year 7月20日|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}, the ordinance was abolished with the implementation of the {{ill|Act on National Holidays|ja|国民の祝日に関する法律|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}} (Law No. 178 of 1948), as stipulated in Article 2 of the supplementary provisions of the act.

