== Overview ==

It was promulgated on {{ill|September 4, 1912|ja|1912nd year 9月4日|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/September 4, 1912|qq=}} (Taisho 1, Imperial Ordinance No. 19) and took effect on the same day. Simultaneously, the previous {{ill|Proclamation on Yearly Public Holidays and Festivals|ja|年中祭日祝日ノ休暇日ヲ定ム|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Proclamation on Yearly Public Holidays and Festivals|qq=}} (Meiji 6, Daijokan Proclamation No. 344) was abolished.

The holidays from the previous proclamation, including {{ill|Genshi-sai|ja|元始祭|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Genshi-sai|qq=}} ({{ill|January 3|ja|1月3日|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/January 3|qq=}}), {{ill|New Year's Banquet|ja|新年宴会|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/New Year's Banquet|qq=}} ({{ill|January 5|ja|1月5日|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/January 5|qq=}}), {{ill|Kigensetsu|ja|紀元節|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kigensetsu|qq=}} ({{ill|February 11|ja|2月11日|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/February 11|qq=}}), {{ill|Jinmu Emperor Festival|ja|神武天皇祭|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jinmu Emperor Festival|qq=}} ({{ill|April 3|ja|4月3日|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/April 3|qq=}}), {{ill|Kannamesai|ja|神嘗祭|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kannamesai|qq=}} ({{ill|October 17|ja|10月17日|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/October 17|qq=}}), {{ill|Niinamesai|ja|新嘗祭|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Niinamesai|qq=}} ({{ill|November 23|ja|11月23日|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/November 23|qq=}}), {{ill|Spring Koryosai|ja|春季皇霊祭|1=Kōreisai|lt=Spring Kōreisai|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Spring Koryosai|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōreisai|qq=}} ({{ill|Spring Equinox|ja|春分|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Spring Equinox|qq=}}), and {{ill|Autumn Koryosai|ja|秋季皇霊祭|1=Kōreisai|lt=Autumn Kōreisai|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Autumn Koryosai|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōreisai|qq=}} ({{ill|Autumn Equinox|ja|秋分|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Autumn Equinox|qq=}}), were retained. 

Due to the demise of {{ill|Emperor Meiji|ja|明治天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Meiji|qq=}} and the accession of {{ill|Emperor Taisho|ja|大正天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Taisho|qq=}}, the {{ill|Previous Emperor Festival|ja|先帝祭|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Previous Emperor Festival|qq=}} was moved from {{ill|Emperor Komei Festival|ja|孝明天皇祭|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Komei Festival|qq=}} ({{ill|January 30|ja|1月30日|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/January 30|qq=}}) to Meiji Emperor Festival ({{ill|July 30|ja|7月30日|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/July 30|qq=}}), and the {{ill|Emperor's Birthday|ja|天皇誕生日|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor's Birthday|qq=}} (Tenchōsetsu) was moved to {{ill|August 31|ja|8月31日|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/August 31|qq=}}.

On {{ill|July 16, 1913|ja|1913rd year 7月16日|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/July 16, 1913|qq=}}, the ordinance was amended (Taisho 2, Imperial Ordinance No. 259)<ref>[https://dl.ndl.go.jp/info:ndljp/pid/2952391/1 官報 1913rd year 7月18日]</ref> to add a {{ill|Tenchōsetsu holiday|ja|天長節祝日|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenchōsetsu holiday|qq=}} ({{ill|October 31|ja|10月31日|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/October 31|qq=}}). The birthday of Emperor Taisho on August 31 was deemed unsuitable for ceremonies due to the summer heat, leading to the establishment of a new ceremonial day while keeping August 31 as a public holiday, thus increasing the number of holidays by one.

On {{ill|March 4, 1927|ja|1927th year 3月4日|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/March 4, 1927|qq=}}, a full revision (Showa 2, Imperial Ordinance No. 25)<ref>[https://dl.ndl.go.jp/info:ndljp/pid/2956510/1 官報 1927th year 3月4日]</ref> added the {{ill|Meiji Setsu|ja|明治節|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji Setsu|qq=}} ({{ill|November 3|ja|11月3日|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/November 3|qq=}}). Following the demise of Emperor Taisho and the accession of {{ill|Emperor Showa|ja|昭和天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Showa|qq=}}, the {{ill|Previous Emperor Festival|ja|先帝祭|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Previous Emperor Festival|qq=}} was moved from the Meiji Emperor Festival to the Taisho Emperor Festival ({{ill|December 25|ja|12月25日|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/December 25|qq=}}), and the Tenchōsetsu was moved to {{ill|April 29|ja|4月29日|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/April 29|qq=}}. The Tenchōsetsu holiday added in 1913 was abolished due to its summer timing. The Meiji Setsu was introduced to offset this loss, maintaining the total number of holidays.

On {{ill|July 20, 1948|ja|1948th year 7月20日|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/July 20, 1948|qq=}}, the ordinance was abolished with the implementation of the {{ill|Act on National Holidays|ja|国民の祝日に関する法律|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Act on National Holidays|qq=}} (Law No. 178 of 1948), as stipulated in Article 2 of the supplementary provisions of the act.

